PHYTOPHTHORA DIEBACK, JUNIPER - UK: (SCOTLAND)
**********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 25 Oct 2015
Source: British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) News [edited]
http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-34626317


Juniper plants in 'critical state'
----------------------------------
A study by Plantlife said juniper was in a "critical state" due to the spread of the deadly fungal disease [caused by] _Phytophthora austrocedrae_. The report followed a survey carried out by amateur enthusiasts. [A] decline of [the] juniper [population] is caused by the failure of bushes -- many of which are over a century old -- to produce seeds.

Once infected, a juniper bush turns orange then brown. The survey found that 63 per cent of bushes surveyed in Scotland have brown patches, and 79 per cent of juniper recorded in 2014 was either mature, old, or dead. Deborah Long, Plantlife Scotland, said: "We know juniper populations are struggling, but they now face an additional threat [with] this new disease."

Murdo Fraser MSP, Conservative politician representing Mid-Scotland and Fife, added: "Juniper is one of our most iconic species. Used not only by birds as cover and food, juniper is a key native plant for human use too. Today though, it is in trouble. Plantlife's report is a call to action for us all to do what we can for juniper."

